hes from historical musicology, urban sociology, and sound studies to shed light on newly surfaced archival material, Fanfare for a City argues that urbanism was a driving force in how nineteenth-century music was produced, performed, and policed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMusiczFrancezParisy19th centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aMusiczFrancezParisy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aOperazFrancezParisy19th century2DLC. 0aOperazFrancezParisy19th century. 0aStreet musicianszFrancezParis2DLC. 0aStreet musicianszFrancezParis. 0aUrbanizationzFrancey19th century2DLC. 0aUrbanizationzFrancey19th century. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520393486?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520393486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520393486/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles